{"blockStates":[{"name":"Dissipative Quantum Systems","uid":"Sticker #17296c8d695","x":6,"y":5,"width":329,"height":553,"marginX":15,"marginY":15,"userText":"The Schr√∂dinger-Langevin-Kostin (SLK) equation describes a dissipative quantum system:\n\n<pre>i&hbar;&part;&Psi;(x,t)/&part;t=[-&hbar;<sup>2</sup>&nabla;<sup>2</sup>/(2m)+V(x,t)+F(x,t)]&Psi;(x,t)</pre>\n\n<p>where &hbar; is the Planck constant, m is the mass of the particle, &Psi; is the wave function, V(x, t) is the potential energy function, x is the coordinate, and t is time. \n\n<p>The dissipative term F(x,t) can be written as:\n\n<pre>F(x,t)=&lambda;[S(x,t)-&lang;S&rang;]</pre>\n\nwith S(x,t) being the phase of the wave function &Psi;(x,t).\n\n<p>This page shows that the energy dissipation can \ngradually rest a harmonic oscillator on the ground state, \nsimilar to what friction does in the world of classical mechanics. The first example sets the initial state to\nbe an excited state. The second example sets the initial\nstate to be a Gaussian wavepacket off the equilibrium\nposition. In both cases, the harmonic oscillator falls\nto the ground state.\n\n<p>As the ground energy has the lowest energy, \ndissipation can be used to implement quantum annealing,\nthe mechanism of a type of quantum computer pioneered\nby D-Wave.","decimals":3,"color":"#808080","textColor":"#ffffff","useHtml":true,"keepResult":false},{"name":"x0","uid":"Slider #1729939a127","x":348,"y":83,"width":100,"height":60,"minimum":-10,"maximum":10,"steps":20,"value":-10,"source":true,"snapToTick":true,"valuePrecision":2},{"name":"Series Block","uid":"Series Block #1729939b60f","x":482,"y":142,"width":60,"height":100,"start":-10,"increment":0.2,"count":100},{"name":"dx","uid":"Slider #172993aa70d","x":347,"y":154,"width":100,"height":60,"minimum":0.1,"maximum":0.2,"steps":10,"value":0.2,"source":true,"snapToTick":true,"valuePrecision":2},{"name":"nx","uid":"Slider #172993b290d","x":347,"y":226,"width":100,"height":60,"minimum":50,"maximum